> Why can't it vary based on instance data? 

I see what you're saying.  I think will be fine for me, but let me look into it.  Anyway, if that's the case, then it should definitely be lowercase `primitive_type`.

> I can't imagine a classproperty being very useful because its output would be essentially fixed. Might as well make it a constant in that case.

It can be handy to compute something based on an inherited value that you want accessible at the class-level:

```python
class MyBaseClass(object):
    @classproperty
    def type_id(cls):
        return "{}.{}".format(cls.__module__, cls.__name__)
```

